### What are Signals?

Signals are a **reactive primitive** introduced in Angular 16+. They provide a granular, efficient way to manage state and react to changes without Zone.js or heavy change detection.

### Creating and Reading Signals

```typescript
import { signal, computed, effect } from '@angular/core';

// Create a writable signal
const count = signal(0);      // Initial value 0

// Read the value
console.log(count());          // 0

// Set a new value
count.set(5);                 // Replace value

// Update based on current value
count.update(value => value + 1);  // Increment
```

### Computed Signals

Derived values that recompute automatically when their dependencies change:

```typescript
const firstName = signal('John');
const lastName = signal('Doe');

// Computed signal — readonly, auto-updating
const fullName = computed(() => `${firstName()} ${lastName()}`);

console.log(fullName());   // 'John Doe'
firstName.set('Jane');
console.log(fullName());   // 'Jane Doe'
```

`computed` is **lazy** and **memoized** — it only recalculates when read and dependencies change.

### Effects

Effects run side effects when signals change:

```typescript
effect(() => {
  console.log(`Count changed to: ${count()}`);
});
```

Effects run automatically within an injection context (e.g., component constructor). They clean up when the component is destroyed.

### Signals in Components

```typescript
@Component({
  template: `
    <p>Count: {{ count() }}</p>
    <p>Double: {{ double() }}</p>
    <button (click)="increment()">+</button>
  `
})
export class CounterComponent {
  count = signal(0);
  double = computed(() => this.count() * 2);

  increment() {
    this.count.update(c => c + 1);
  }
}
```

### set() vs update()

- **`set(value)`** — Replaces the signal value entirely: `count.set(10)`.
- **`update(fn)`** — Derives new value from current: `count.update(v => v + 1)`.

### Signal-based Inputs and Model

Angular 17.2+ introduced signal-based inputs:

```typescript
@Component({...})
export class UserCard {
  // Signal-based @Input
  name = input<string>();                // Optional
  age = input(0, { alias: 'userAge' }); // With default

  // Two-way signal binding (replaces @Output + EventEmitter)
  selected = model(false);

  toggle() {
    this.selected.update(v => !v);
  }
}
```

```html
<!-- Usage -->
<app-user-card [name]="userName" [(selected)]="isSelected" />
```

### Performance Benefits

- **Fine-grained reactivity** — Only components that use a signal re-render when it changes.
- **No Zone.js dependency** — Signals can work without Zone.js, reducing overhead.
- **No unnecessary checks** — Unlike the default change detection that checks the whole tree.
- **Predictable** — Signal updates are synchronous and deterministic.

codeExample:
import { signal, computed, effect } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  template: `
    <p>{{ firstName() }} {{ lastName() }}</p>
    <p>Full: {{ fullName() }}</p>
    <input [value]="firstName()" (input)="firstName.set($any($event.target).value)">
  `
})
export class NameComponent {
  firstName = signal('John');
  lastName = signal('Doe');
  fullName = computed(() => `${this.firstName()} ${this.lastName()}`);

  constructor() {
    effect(() => console.log('Name:', this.fullName()));
  }
}
